Plateau State governor,  Simon Lalong,  has said that  the profiling and return of almajirai has commenced and shall continue until the last almajiri is relocated while the first batch of 279 almajiris had been returned to their states. He said a total number of  243 almajirai were sent to their states of Bauchi, Kano and Kaduna, while 36 were sent to their local governments in Wase and Kanam noting that starting from 4th May 2020, all citizens shall be required to use facemasks in public places in addition to observing all hygiene and social distancing regulations. The governor made the disclosure during a broadcast to the people of the state yesterday. He said further to the efforts at combating COVID-19,  the total lockdown which resumed midnight Sunday April 26th 2020, shall be relaxed from Midnight of Thursday, 30th April 2020, to  Midnight of Sunday, 3rd May 2020 to enable people again re-stock their homes. According to him, this will henceforth be the pattern until further review, in order words, the period of restocking will last from midnight of every Thursday to midnight of every Sunday, noting  that in addition to the total lockdown which restricts movement in and out of the state, and in order to curb community spread of COVID-19, government has decided to close all intra-State borders with effect from 4th May 2020. He added that there would be no movement from one local government to another even during the period, except for those on essential services as earlier enumerated stressing  that with the COVID-19 index case confirmed in Plateau State, government  certainly have to redouble efforts at combating the pandemic by cutting off community transmission and blocking more imported cases. The governor added that the only way they can do this is to encourage and sustain preventive measures, which cannot succeed with stigmatisation and discrimination noting that Corona Virus is not a death sentence and scientific evidence suggests that there is high survival rate among those infected. He appeal to citizens to avoid stigmatizing people who are either quarantined, suspected or confirmed to have the disease.  